Here's the registration setup:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // One HttpClient + data service for the whole app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // Fresh ViewModel per navigation to avoid stale state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Fresh page per navigation (each gets its own ViewModel)
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reuse one instance to avoid socket exhaustion. Thread-safe by design. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient`, stateless request logic — one instance is sufficient and efficient. |
| `MainViewModel` / `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Each navigation should get a fresh VM so you never show stale data or leftover UI state from a previous visit. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Pairs with its ViewModel — a new page instance per navigation avoids visual artifacts and stale bindings. |

**Key rule of thumb:** services that hold no per-request state → **Singleton**. UI-layer objects (pages, ViewModels) that carry user-facing state → **Transient** so each navigation starts clean.

> If your `DataService` ever held per-user session state (e.g., a token cache), you'd consider `Scoped` — but in MAUI, scoped and singleton behave identically unless you manually create scopes, so singleton is the practical default for shared services.
